+## First-class GeoDataFrame validation
+
+The `pandera.geopandas` module provides geospatial counterparts of the
+pandas object-based and class-based APIs:
+{py:class}`~pandera.api.geopandas.container.GeoDataFrameSchema` and
+{py:class}`~pandera.api.geopandas.model.GeoDataFrameModel`. Validating
+with either always returns a {py:class}`~geopandas.GeoDataFrame` — with
+the active geometry column and CRS metadata intact — even when the input
+is a plain {py:class}`~pandas.DataFrame` whose geometry column needs to
+be coerced:
+
+```{code-cell} python
+import pandas as pd
+import pandera.geopandas as pa
+
+schema = pa.GeoDataFrameSchema({
+    "geometry": pa.Column(pa.Geometry(crs="EPSG:4326"), coerce=True),
+    "region": pa.Column(str),
+})
+
+df = pd.DataFrame({
+    "geometry": ["POINT (30 10)", "POINT (10 30)"],
+    "region": ["NA", "SA"],
+})
+
+validated = schema.validate(df)
+print(type(validated), validated.crs)
+```
+
+The class-based API works the same way:
+
+```{code-cell} python
+class GeoModel(pa.GeoDataFrameModel):
+    geometry: pa.GeoSeries
+    region: str = pa.Field(isin=["NA", "SA"])
+
+
+GeoModel.validate(validated)
+```
+
+Geo schemas are first-class citizens of the rest of the pandera
+toolchain: they can be serialized to JSON/YAML and loaded back (the
+loaded schema still returns a `GeoDataFrame`), inferred from data with
+`pandera.geopandas.infer_schema`, and geo models can be used as pydantic
+model fields via `pandera.typing.geopandas.GeoDataFrame[GeoModel]`.
+
+## Validating GeoDataFrames with pandas schemas
+
+You can also use plain pandas schemas to validate geodataframes. In the example
 below we'll use the {ref}`class-based API <dataframe-models>` to define a
 {py:class}`~pandera.api.pandas.model.DataFrameModel` for validation.
 
